    <segment id="1" parent="44" relname="span">Intuitiveness and transparency are interrelated attributes of a product.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="35" relname="span"> 
The transparency of a product relates to how easily users of a product understands the mental model, or logical process flow, of that product.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="4" relname="circumstance"> 
For example, when a user hits the top of a television when the reception is poor, </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="31" relname="span">
they have a poor mental model of television technology. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="30" relname="span">
Decades ago, this model was true. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="means">
By striking the television on its top or sides, </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="29" relname="span">
the electronic tubes inside the television might reset or reseat, allowing the picture to come back. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="32" relname="span">
However, with solid state electronics, this is no longer true. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="33" relname="span">

The intuitive nature of a product refers, I believe, to how readily the usability of product reflects the same mental model of a product.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="sequence"> 
For example, the mental model of a telephone involves 
picking up the receiver, </segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="sequence">
dialing the number, </segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="11" relname="sequence">
waiting for someone to answer, </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="11" relname="sequence">
conversing, </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="11" relname="sequence">
and then hanging up the receiver. </segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="39" relname="contrast">
The transparent pieces of the model are the miles of telephone lines and many sattelites floating above the Earth that support this mental model.</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="40" relname="span"> 
The intuitive nature of the product is that the model is so transparent, </segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="17" relname="elaboration">
all someone needs to do to call someone is simple push the right sequence of buttons on the telephone. </segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="43" relname="span">

Comparing land lines to cell phones leads to another question on intuitiveness. </segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="21" relname="preparation">
As the professor stated, </segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="38" relname="span">
learned behavior to a similar mental model can lead to varied results. </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="37" relname="span">
To dial from a cell phone, 
users must typically press one additional keystroke to actually active the phone call. </segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="34" relname="list">
Since a) this keystroke is not required on land line, the prelearned model, </segment>
    <segment id="25" parent="34" relname="list">
and b) this key is not positioned in the same location on all cell phones, </segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="23" relname="span">
many users have issues with the intuitive nature of cell phones. </segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="28" relname="concession">
Once connected, using a cell phone is no different than a land line. </segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="36" relname="span">
However, it is with the single additional keystroke that intuitiveness is lost.</segment>
